8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 654, L.D. 1007, “An Act to Update the
10 State's Informed Consent Laws Regarding Drug-induced Abortion”
11 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
12 following:
13 'Sec. 1. 22 MRSA §1599-A, sub-§3 is enacted to read:
14 3. Informed consent for medication abortion. In addition to providing the woman
15 with the information in subsection 2, if an abortion will be induced using any drug or
16 combination of drugs, referred to in this subsection as a "medication abortion," the health
17 care professional, as defined in section 1596, subsection 1, paragraph C, shall inform the
18 woman orally and in writing, in a manner that in the health care professional's professional
19 judgment is not misleading and that will be understood by the patient, of at least the
20 following:
21 A. That it may be possible, with varying degrees of effectiveness depending on the
22 individual circumstances of the patient, to reverse the effects of the medication
23 abortion; and
24 B. Information about how the woman can locate a health care professional who
25 provides medication abortion reversal services.
26 The health care professional shall document in the patient's record that the information
27 required by this subsection was provided to the woman, and whether the information was
28 provided orally or in writing, before initiating the medication abortion.'
29 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
30 number to read consecutively.
31 SUMMARY
3322 This amendment, which is the minority report of the committee, replaces the bill. The
3333 amendment requires that, before initiating a medication abortion, a health care professional
3344 document in a patient's record that the health care professional informed the patient either
